<T1>north korea's underground nuclear testing presents significant monitoring challenges and geopolitical risks.</T1>

<T1.1>global sensors can detect a nuclear test almost immediately.</T1.1>
<T1.1.1>the comprehensive nuclear-test-ban treaty organization operates over 300 monitoring stations worldwide.</T1.1.1>
<T1.1.2>seismic technology can distinguish manmade explosions from natural earthquakes.</T1.1.2>
<T1.1.3>noble gas sensors can detect radiation even if no fallout escapes the tunnel.</T1.1.3>

<T1.2>key details about the test often remain unknown to outside analysts.</T1.2>
<T1.2.1>the exact size of the explosion may never be conclusively determined.</T1.2.1>
<T1.2.2>whether plutonium or uranium was used as fissile material is difficult to confirm.</T1.2.2>
<T1.2.3>the number of devices tested simultaneously can be obscured.</T1.2.3>

<T1.3>north korea conducts underground tests to advance its weapons program.</T1.3>
<T1.3.1>tests help pyongyang perfect technology to miniaturize warheads for missiles.</T1.3.1>
<T1.3.1.1>a third test could provide data needed to fit warheads onto delivery systems.</T1.3.1.1>
<T1.3.2>north korea is the only country to conduct nuclear tests since 1998.</T1.3.2>
<T1.3.2.1>previous underground tests occurred in 2006 and 2009.</T1.3.2.1>

<T1.4>satellite imagery reveals preparation of north korea's test site.</T1.4>
<T1.4.1>a third tunnel has been prepared in the punggye-ri area.</T1.4.1>
<T1.4.2>construction began in 2009 and is now largely completed.</T1.4.2>
<T1.4.3>the new tunnel is estimated to be one kilometer long and 380 meters deep.</T1.4.3>

<T1.5>underground testing carries inherent risks of radioactive release.</T1.5>
<T1.5.1>north korea's 2006 test leaked radiation detected 4,500 miles away in canada.</T1.5.1>
<T1.5.2>the u.s. experienced 150 cases of radiation release during its underground testing program.</T1.5.2>
<T1.5.3>larger devices increase the risk of fissures or blowouts from the tunnel.</T1.5.3>
<T1.5.3.1>a blowout would release radioactive clouds and create political storms in northeast asia.</T1.5.3.1>

<T1.6>north korea's nuclear program escalates regional security concerns.</T1.6>
<T1.6.1>december's successful long-range rocket launch demonstrated missile technology advances.</T1.6.1>
<T1.6.1.1>analysts suggest parts of the united states are now within missile range.</T1.6.1.1>
<T1.6.2>pyongyang plans further long-range rocket launches despite u.n. condemnation.</T1.6.2>
<T1.6.3>additional tests would vastly increase the threat to northeast asian security.</T1.6.3>
